x4freetext: data (elastic+diff.elastic cs). See HISTORY for detail
Data have been calculated by means of the optical and
statistical model with consideration of preequilibrium
emission, using a consistent set of parameters based
as much as possible on experimental data.
The nuclear model parameters were adjusted not only
to reproduce the experimental cross sections, but
also to be consistent with other nuclear data as
strength functions, resonance densities and level
schemes. for nuclear reaction data, the corresponding
references are given below under REL-REF. In several
cases the data have been renormalized to recent values
of the respective standard cross sections.
Single-channel optical model, code ABACUS II
- Reactions with particles in the exit channel ...
20 keV to 20 MeV with the following exception;
Capture and partial inelastic scattering cross
sections to low excited states are only given up to
6 MeV (at most) because of the limited range of
validity of the models employed. (for the high
energy part of these reactions, direct-semidirect
calculations by the same authors are in progress.)
Up to the energy of the highest discrete level the
elastic cross-sections were calculated as sum of

was neglected. Although the overall effect is small,
the angular distribution for the lowest energy where
this neglect took place may be inaccurate.
